Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the finest relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in a Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands straddled between the ends of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The entire building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the vaulted ceiling, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the westernmost passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retard in the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway that ran to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Its isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
British and dominating forces advanced out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly gone into disrepair, largely surpassed by history.
But nowadays, this rail route to Anatolia and all the points to the east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-growing diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new commitment policy.
Notably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I embarked on the wagon for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the main foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish deputy Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy ride along the tracks that produced the ancient world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intending to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-built shopping malls and power bakeries, where managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early morning contracts.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost every other political party in Europe.
Dress, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
“The aim of the foreign policy party is now to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbours.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he says.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today it has to look east and west at the same time.
This was not the case for one or the other.
They must be both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want where to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost everyone I spoke to here played out of memory: the ties of not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, the whole of Europe can metaphorically travel those railway lines eastward through Asia and into the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpasha station, after another blank night, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe's Middle Eastern ambitions can now be largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I wait at the terminal for the ferry that takes me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At that time, at least, there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent should make claims on this fascinating country.
