The "bee car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking for example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in vehicles of the manufacturer.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the bee's compound eyes, able to see in all directions with an angle greater than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, the engineers developed what they called a location laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism detects obstacles that are in front of the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately, allows to prevent the collision.
“The moment it detects an obstacle, the small robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at right angles or greater to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and lead engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deflect up or down, nor even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can rotate and not exploiting endless directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require the storing of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, for this it can work without interruptions and with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to the destination avoiding obstacles present in the path.
