MUFG will also invest US$6 billion in convertible securities at a conversion price of US$31.25, ensuring a return of 10%.
Morgan Stanley said the global transaction would be based on an average price of $29 per share, a percentage lower than its current price of 28%.
At around 5:00 p.m., Morgan Stanley fell 6.79% to $23.07.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to a bank holding company,” said John Mack, CEO of Morgan Stanley.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to differentiate its shares by passing them under the control of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with the MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than previously assumed.
The terms defined on Monday also show that in recent days the agreement has been modified: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced the sale of 20% of its shares to the Japanese giant for an amount equal to $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, in Tokyo, Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of MUFG, explained: “We thought that our shareholding would be exclusively composed of ordinary shares.
But considering the current situation of the world economy and the market, we have chosen to minimize the risks and protect ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will obtain Morgan Stanley securities at a price below their book value of 7%.
And the transaction would result in an investment of at least 20% of equity on a diluted basis.”
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert in one year half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares if, during a given period, the latter are traded more than 50% below the fixed conversion price, or at about 47 dollars.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital contributed by MUFG would allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokesman for the group, however, declined to clarify the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is therefore expected to set a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" lightened its budget since the end of August.
The past few weeks have put a strain on the group, which has seen the value of its shares halved while the cost of risk insurance has soared.
Cost that reflowed on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” among the big Wall Street investment banks after the collapse of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Warren Buffett’s Berkshire Hathaway.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
To found the republic on a socialism right in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to the official results, 64% of the voters voted "yes" to the referendum, on a basis of votes equal to 80%.
According to these results, the "no" vote was 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, it would have to get half of the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed victory over his draft constitution on Sunday and Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously," he said, congratulating Ecuadorians in the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The scrutiny, which was carried out calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a text of 444 points aimed at consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution enshrined the state's power over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially from the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants greater power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive terms of four years, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced his intention to take advantage of this amendment and to resubmit his candidacy for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also states the free health and education services, which the president has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, a provision that will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando has launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive in the desert for ten days were brought back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently fit, the hostages arrived at the Almaza military base, near Cairo’s international airport, at around 3:30 p.m., aboard a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were transferred immediately, without being able to give any interviews to the press, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They enjoy “good health” and no ransom was paid “to the kidnappers,” Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the runway.
Abducted on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been rammed from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the organizing agency of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night just before dawn.
“There were shootings, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled,” said the official, who asked to remain anonymous.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We have to admit that if we have achieved this result it has been thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our intelligence services, of the special forces," he said, without adding further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were found and to have killed six, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and to have captured two.
According to the army, the kidnappers were linked to a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), a claim immediately denied by the latter.
The Silent Majority of Culture
On the front page a debate on the financing of culture on which the current election campaign focuses.
That's good.
But a part of our cultural life always remains in the shadows.
Who will speak out to denounce the pitiful sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that starve?
Which politician will dare remind the federal government that it is neglecting monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, do we not have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is paying 3.5 million euros for the restoration of the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbors, it is the Constitution that states that heritage protection is part of the national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, by every political authority and by every government department, and all this by common accord.
In Quebec, at the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, there are at least 40,000 volunteers who, grouped into 211 societies for the preservation of the historical, genealogical, archives and patrimonial assets, preserve, for four bucks, private archives and archaeological sites.
It is they who often defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-making bodies attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help by partial nationalization the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which ended up in difficulty first in Europe due to the crisis of the American credit market: the three nations will provide 11.2 billion euros to the financial institution - insurance with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level over the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been debated for more than a year is that of Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard can constitute a precedent.
Under the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank’s share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its interests, including first and foremost the assets, mainly insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis shares had started with a vertical collapse, serious signs of crisis of the institute had then presented themselves in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank’s shares fell nearly 12% on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Considering the current stock prices the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank’s executives this value is not real.
The company blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US plan of 700 billion dollars.
On Monday, the title slowly rose again.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed the bank’s new CEO.
The financial institution has also looked for private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a deserving offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors should not be afraid of losing money.
There was no panic among the bank’s customers, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns autonomous subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox,” writes the Washington Post, quoting Richard Dick, author of the program to follow drug prescriptions.
The insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in case of claims to the health of the possible customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not take out the insurance.
A long time ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was only concluded after the result of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification code of the customer you can easily get information from pharmacies about what medicines he bought in the last year and a half and from this the program evidences what diseases he suffers and in what health condition he is.
For example, if you regularly purchase large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this means that your blood fat level is in practice incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, to the insurer therefore besides paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines are usable for several purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the point of view of insurance - commercial, applies as a factor of increased risk, the first two do not.
For the request and data processing, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, request the approval of the patient.
The authorities now oblige them to do so even though they have not so far imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies have recently also processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to the data of medicine consumption in order to provide a more accurate picture of the state of health of the patients.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time controlling usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives supervisory authority to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: that is why he has developed a program that links data forwarding with the express approval of the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
Global Marseilles menu
EU and India to double trade
Since the European Union and India are mainly trading partners, the agenda of the ninth summit was dominated by this theme as well as all other global issues.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit that will deal first and foremost with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is becoming a major democratic power that should be given more voice in international affairs, but member countries have yet to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So this issue was not insisted on at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, in his capacity as President of the Union, José Manuel Barroso, chairman of the commission, and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade in five years, i.e. up to 100 billion euros.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not a too ambitious goal.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also take off in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the deal.
The objective is to balance because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi instead is only ninth among the EU partners.
The summit focused on global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms by both sides, and called for the convening of a UN conference.
They urged the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both sides have played a role in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed its persistence in the energy and climate agenda, i.e. wants to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as on the need to conclude a global pact at the climate conference scheduled for next year and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb the rise in food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Prime Minister of India will travel to the French capital today where in a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris it is hoped that to build the Indian nuclear reactors the French companies will receive an order worth 20 billion euros.
According to information from our news agency the agreement would last 15 years.
In Frankfurt more than three hundred Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
There will be over three hundred Italian publishers present at the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international event for the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair awaits more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 different countries who will occupy the 171,790 square meters of the Fair with more than 403,000 titles on display and with Turkey as guest of honor.
The Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities Francesco Maria Giro will represent the Italian Government at the inauguration ceremony of the Italian Pavilion: Italy will be institutionally present with a Punto Italia - 264 square meters of exhibition space.
The meeting with the press at Room Struktur in Hall 5.0 of the Buchmesse will be followed: this will be the opportunity to present figures, trends and perspectives on the state of publishing in Italy.
According to the data, the weight of books by foreign authors is gradually decreasing on the total Italian production, and in particular on that for adults and young people.
Steve Fossett's plane found, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a 3,000-metre high plateau in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the aircraft, however, there were no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is exactly what Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff said no human remains were found either on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was reported dead in February.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Safety (NTSB) said a team of investigators had been dispatched hours after the wreck was spotted and identified the aircraft: the Bellanca 8kcab, which had been missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett’s personal belongings had been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two Fossett-named documents, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, of cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search was halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of primates.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete the round the world flight on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later he had circled the world by plane and without stopping.
Among his many records, he also flew at 15,445 meters above the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect
An off-the-shelf SUV with an original design and well defined by sharp lines, wide surfaces and sharp corners.
This is, in summary, Glk the latest born among the offroad "compact" of the house of the star with which Mercedes-Benz has tried to give a breath of fresh air in this sector.
Precisely for its contents outside the traditional canons, the communication that will accompany the launch of the Glk SUV, available at Mercedes-Benz showrooms from next October 17, will also be unexpected and unconventional.
Thus, the hype that will accompany the debut of the new car will launch an unprecedented mode of communication also through a futuristic 3D poster campaign, used for the first time in Italy by an automotive brand.
A project of maxi-displays, divided into three different phases, that will dominate the very central Milanese shopping street, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication will begin with the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision and thanks to special glasses distributed near Corso Como it will be possible to see the new SUV in almost real size and in three-dimensional format.
In fact, looking at the image you will have the impression that the car comes out of the poster.
Subsequently, through the use of the innovative technology Elumina8 the new Glk will be illuminated at different times in all its details, and then recomposed in a single image.
Undoubtedly Mercedes with this advertising is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of automotive communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to stir the interest of future buyers? We will see.
